<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,356,1409,1435]" box="[151,356,1409,1435]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,356,1409,1435]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,356,1409,1435]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<taxonomicName box="[151,291,1409,1435]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Cercosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,291,1409,1435]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Cercosaura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 2
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1479,1685]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,398,1479,1504]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
The first specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[670,801,1480,1503]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Cercosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[670,801,1480,1503]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Cercosaura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 2 were only recorded recently (in 2009) and, as the preceding one, it is under study as part of the revision of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[903,1034,1517,1540]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Cercosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[903,1034,1517,1540]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Cercosaura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1479,1685]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,503,1551,1576]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[513,644,1552,1575]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Cercosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[513,644,1552,1575]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Cercosaura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 2 is endemic to Brazilian 
<taxonomicName box="[998,1116,1551,1576]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="15" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, and until now only known from the Jamanxim river system (
<figureCitation box="[540,611,1588,1613]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1702,1724]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,447,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[150,1436,437,1684]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 9. Distribution of examined material of Cercosaura oshaughnessyi, C. parkeri, Cercosaura sp. 2, Cercosaura sp. 3, Cercosaura sp. 4, Gymnophthalmus leucomystax, and Gymnophthalmus sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581984/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), state of 
<collectingRegion box="[727,780,1588,1612]" country="Suriname" name="Para" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Pará</collectingRegion>
. It is terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits dense ombrophilous terra firme forest, where it is found on the ground (Mendes-Pinto &amp; Souza 2011—identified as 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Cercosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ocellata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Cercosaura ocellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
